.TH _PRINTF 3 "APRIL 2026" "Holberton School" "Custom Printf Manual"
.SH NAME
_printf \- formatted output conversion
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B #include "main.h"
.sp
.BI "int _printf(const char *" format ", ...);"
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B _printf
function produces output according to a
.I format
string. This implementation uses a local buffer of 1024 characters to minimize the number of calls to the
.BR write (2)
system call.
.SH FORMAT STRING
The format string is composed of zero or more directives: ordinary characters (not
.B %
), which are copied unchanged to the output stream; and conversion specifications, each of which results in fetching zero or more subsequent arguments.
.SH CONVERSION SPECIFIERS
The following specifiers are supported:
.TP
.B c
Prints a single character.
.TP
.B s
Prints a string of characters. If the pointer is NULL, prints "(null)".
.TP
.B d, i
Prints a signed decimal integer.
.TP
.B b
The unsigned int argument is converted to binary notation.
.TP
.B u
Prints an unsigned decimal integer.
.TP
.B o
Prints an unsigned octal integer.
.TP
.B x, X
Prints an unsigned hexadecimal integer.
.B x
uses lowercase (abcdef) and
.B X
uses uppercase (ABCDEF).
.TP
.B S
Prints a string. Non-printable characters (0 < ASCII < 32 or >= 127) are printed as \\x followed by the ASCII code value in hexadecimal (upper case - always 2 characters).
.TP
.B %
A literal '%' is written.
.SH RETURN VALUE
Upon success,
.B _printf
returns the number of characters printed. If
.I format
is NULL, it returns \-1.
.SH EXAMPLES
.B _printf("Binary of 5: %b\\n", 5);
.br
Output: Binary of 5: 101
.sp
.B _printf("%S\\n", "Best\\nSchool");
.br
Output: Best\\x0ASchool
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR printf (3),
.IR write (2)
